// ── Retina · BCSC Section 12 · Part 1 · Fluorescein & ICG Angiography
// Source: BCSC Section 12 (Retina and Vitreous), Ch. 2 (Diagnostic Approach).
const BCSC_FFA_RECALL: RecallQ[] = [
  { id: 1, question: "What wavelengths do the excitation and barrier filters transmit in fluorescein angiography?", answer: "Excitation filter: blue-green light at 465–490 nm (fluorescein's peak excitation). Barrier filter: yellow-green at 520–530 nm (fluorescein's peak emission). The barrier filter blocks essentially all visible wavelengths except the light emitted by fluorescein." },
  { id: 2, question: "What percentage of fluorescein is protein-bound, and why does that matter?", answer: "About 80% is protein-bound. The intact blood–retina barrier prevents fluorescein from diffusing into retinal tissue, so normal retinal vessels do not leak. Dye leaks only where a blood–ocular barrier is absent (new vessels) or defective (inflammation, ischemia)." },
  { id: 3, question: "From which structure does fluorescein readily leak, and what limits its use for choroidal imaging?", answer: "It leaks readily from the fenestrated choriocapillaris, staining surrounding tissue. That rapid leakage, plus light absorption and scattering by RPE and choroidal pigment, limits fluorescein's usefulness for choroidal imaging — ICG is preferred there." },
  { id: 4, question: "Describe the timing of the phases of a normal fluorescein angiogram.", answer: "Choroidal (prearterial) flush ~8–12 s; retinal arterial phase 11–18 s; arteriovenous phase 1–3 s later (with laminar venous flow); complete venous filling over the next 5–10 s; recirculation/mid phase at 2–4 min; late phase at 4–5 min (gradual dye elimination)." },
  { id: 5, question: "What is laminar venous flow on FA?", answer: "Thin columns of dye seen along the walls of the larger veins during the early arteriovenous phase before the veins fill completely — a consequence of the parabolic flow profile (faster central, slower peripheral wall flow)." },
  { id: 6, question: "Why does the fovea appear dark on fluorescein angiography?", answer: "Three reasons: macular xanthophyll pigment absorbs the blue excitation light; the foveal RPE cells are taller and contain more melanin than peripheral RPE; and there are no retinal vessels in the foveal avascular zone." },
  { id: 7, question: "What are the two major categories of FA abnormality?", answer: "Hypofluorescence (reduced or absent fluorescence) and hyperfluorescence (abnormally excessive fluorescence)." },
  { id: 8, question: "What are the two patterns of hypofluorescence?", answer: "Vascular filling defects (nonperfusion or obstruction of an artery, vein, or capillary — seen as delayed or absent filling) and blocked fluorescence (obstruction of the excitation or emitted light by pigment, blood, or fibrous tissue)." },
  { id: 9, question: "How can blocked fluorescence be used to determine a lesion's depth?", answer: "By relating the level of blocked fluorescence to the retinal circulation. If a lesion blocks the choroidal fluorescence but retinal vessels are seen coursing over it, the lesion lies above the choroid and beneath the retinal vessels." },
  { id: 10, question: "What are the four patterns of hyperfluorescence?", answer: "Leakage, staining, pooling, and transmission (window) defect." },
  { id: 11, question: "Define leakage and its behavior over the course of an FA.", answer: "A gradual, marked increase in fluorescence from seepage of dye across a compromised blood–retina barrier. Both brightness and size increase through the study and the borders become indistinct (e.g., CNV, neovascularization, active inflammation)." },
  { id: 12, question: "Define staining and how to recognize it.", answer: "Fluorescein entering solid tissue or material that retains dye — scar, drusen, vessel walls, optic nerve tissue, sclera. Fluorescence increases in brightness through transit and persists in late frames, but the borders remain fixed and intact (size does not change)." },
  { id: 13, question: "Define pooling and give a classic example.", answer: "Accumulation of dye within a fluid-filled space whose margins trap it, producing distinct borders (round/oval). Classic example: pooling under a serous RPE or neurosensory detachment in central serous chorioretinopathy." },
  { id: 14, question: "Define a transmission (window) defect and its time course.", answer: "A view of normal choroidal fluorescence through an RPE pigment defect. It appears early with choroidal filling, peaks with peak choroidal filling, does NOT enlarge, and fades in late frames as choroidal dye is diluted; the dye stays in the choroid and does not enter the retina." },
  { id: 15, question: "Summarize how brightness and size change over time for the four hyperfluorescence patterns.", answer: "Leakage: brightness ↑, size ↑. Staining: brightness ↑, size unchanged (irregular shape). Pooling: brightness same/↑, size unchanged (regular round/oval). Window defect: brightness decreases late, size unchanged." },
  { id: 16, question: "What is the inner blood–retina barrier, and what happens when it is compromised?", answer: "The tight junctions of the retinal vascular endothelium. When compromised, dye leaks through vessel walls into the retinal parenchyma and cystoid spaces (e.g., cystoid macular edema)." },
  { id: 17, question: "What is the outer blood–retina barrier, and what is the effect of its breakdown?", answer: "The retinal pigment epithelium (its tight junctions). When compromised, dye traverses the RPE into the subretinal space or neurosensory retina." },
  { id: 18, question: "What is the classic FA appearance of cystoid macular edema?", answer: "Late pooling of dye in petalloid cystoid spaces radiating from the central macula (Henle fiber layer), often with late staining of the optic nerve head — as seen in postsurgical (Irvine–Gass) CME." },
  { id: 19, question: "Contrast the FA appearance of classic versus occult CNV.", answer: "Classic CNV: an early, well-defined lacy hyperfluorescent network that leaks progressively, with pooling/leakage in the late phase. Occult CNV: poorly defined late leakage and staining without a discrete early network." },
  { id: 20, question: "What temporary and common adverse effects follow fluorescein injection?", answer: "Temporary yellowing of the skin and conjunctiva (6–12 h) and yellow-green urine; nausea and vomiting in ~5% (passes within seconds); and urticaria/hives in ~5% (treated with diphenhydramine unless very mild)." },
  { id: 21, question: "What serious adverse effects can occur with FA, and how is the risk managed?", answer: "Rare hypotension, shock, laryngeal spasm, and even death (~1:222,000). A physician should be on the premises and a crash cart available. Prior urticarial reactions raise the risk; premedication with antihistamines and/or corticosteroids reduces it." },
  { id: 22, question: "How is fluorescein extravasation managed, and what are the pregnancy/lactation considerations?", answer: "Extravasation into the skin is painful and treated with ice-cold compresses for 5–10 minutes and close follow-up until edema/pain/redness resolve. No teratogenicity is proven, but FA is generally avoided in the first trimester unless necessary; fluorescein is excreted in breast milk during lactation." },
  { id: 23, question: "What properties of indocyanine green make it ideal for choroidal imaging?", answer: "ICG is a water-soluble tricarbocyanine dye that is ~98% protein-bound, so it diffuses poorly through the choriocapillaris fenestrations and remains intravascular — ideal for imaging choroidal vessels. Its near-infrared excitation/emission also penetrates RPE, pigment, and blood better than fluorescein." },
  { id: 24, question: "What are ICG's excitation and emission wavelengths, and how is it cleared?", answer: "Excitation ~790–805 nm and emission ~825–835 nm, both in the near-infrared range. ICG is metabolized in the liver and excreted into the bile." },
  { id: 25, question: "Describe the phases of a normal ICG angiogram.", answer: "Early phase: first appearance of dye in the choroidal circulation (large choroidal arteries and veins plus retinal vessels visible). Middle phase (5–15 min): choroidal veins become indistinct with diffuse homogeneous choroidal fluorescence and reduced retinal vessel fluorescence. Late phase (~15 min): little retinal or choroidal detail remains." },
];

const BCSC_FFA_MCQ: MCQ[] = [
  { id: 1, question: "The excitation filter of a fundus camera set up for fluorescein angiography transmits light at:", options: ["520–530 nm yellow-green", "465–490 nm blue-green", "790–805 nm near-infrared", "620–640 nm red"], correct: 1, explanation: "The excitation filter passes blue-green light (465–490 nm, peak excitation); the barrier filter passes yellow-green light (520–530 nm, peak emission)." },
  { id: 2, question: "The barrier filter transmits light at approximately:", options: ["465–490 nm", "520–530 nm", "825–835 nm", "400–450 nm"], correct: 1, explanation: "The barrier filter passes fluorescein's emitted yellow-green light at 520–530 nm and blocks other visible wavelengths." },
  { id: 3, question: "Approximately what fraction of circulating fluorescein is protein-bound?", options: ["20%", "50%", "80%", "98%"], correct: 2, explanation: "Fluorescein is ~80% protein-bound; the free fraction fluoresces and can leak where barriers are defective. (ICG, by contrast, is ~98% bound.)" },
  { id: 4, question: "Fluorescein does NOT normally leak from retinal vessels because of:", options: ["Its large molecular size", "The intact inner blood–retina barrier (tight junctions of retinal endothelium)", "Rapid hepatic clearance", "Binding to RPE melanin"], correct: 1, explanation: "The inner blood–retina barrier (retinal vascular endothelial tight junctions) keeps dye intravascular in healthy retina." },
  { id: 5, question: "On a normal FA, the choroid typically begins to fill at:", options: ["1–3 seconds", "8–12 seconds", "20–25 seconds", "2–4 minutes"], correct: 1, explanation: "The choroidal flush appears at ~8–12 s, about a half-second before the retinal circulation; retinal arteries fill at 11–18 s." },
  { id: 6, question: "\"Laminar flow\" on fluorescein angiography refers to:", options: ["Uniform bright filling of the arteries", "Thin columns of dye along the walls of the larger veins during early venous filling", "Leakage from the choriocapillaris", "Dye pooling under the RPE"], correct: 1, explanation: "Laminar venous flow is the early arteriovenous-phase appearance of dye along vein walls before complete venous filling." },
  { id: 7, question: "The late phase of FA (gradual dye elimination) occurs at approximately:", options: ["15–18 seconds", "1 minute", "4–5 minutes", "20 minutes"], correct: 2, explanation: "Recirculation begins at 2–4 min, and the late phase (dye elimination) is seen at ~4–5 min." },
  { id: 8, question: "The fovea appears hypofluorescent (dark) on FA for all of the following reasons EXCEPT:", options: ["Macular xanthophyll pigment absorbs excitation light", "Taller foveal RPE cells with more melanin", "Absence of vessels in the foveal avascular zone", "A thickened internal limiting membrane at the fovea"], correct: 3, explanation: "The dark fovea reflects xanthophyll pigment, denser foveal RPE melanin, and the avascular FAZ — not the ILM." },
  { id: 9, question: "Hypofluorescence on FA is caused by which two mechanisms?", options: ["Leakage and staining", "Pooling and window defect", "Vascular filling defect and blocked fluorescence", "Transmission defect and leakage"], correct: 2, explanation: "The two hypofluorescence patterns are vascular filling (perfusion) defects and blocked fluorescence." },
  { id: 10, question: "A pigmented lesion blocks fluorescence, but retinal vessels are seen coursing over it. This localizes the lesion to:", options: ["The inner retina", "Anterior to the choroid, deep to the retinal vessels", "The vitreous cavity", "The optic nerve head"], correct: 1, explanation: "Depth is judged by which vessels are obscured; retinal vessels visible over a blocked choroid place the lesion between the two layers." },
  { id: 11, question: "Which hyperfluorescence pattern increases in BOTH brightness and size over the course of the study?", options: ["Staining", "Pooling", "Leakage", "Window defect"], correct: 2, explanation: "Leakage progressively increases in both brightness and area, with indistinct borders." },
  { id: 12, question: "A lesion that brightens through transit and persists late but keeps fixed, intact borders represents:", options: ["Leakage", "Staining", "Pooling", "Filling defect"], correct: 1, explanation: "Staining is dye entering solid retained material (scar, drusen, vessel wall, sclera, optic nerve) with unchanging borders." },
  { id: 13, question: "Late accumulation of dye within a serous RPE detachment, with sharply demarcated borders, is best described as:", options: ["Staining", "Pooling", "Window defect", "Blocked fluorescence"], correct: 1, explanation: "Pooling is dye trapped in a fluid-filled space with distinct margins, classically the RPE detachment of central serous chorioretinopathy." },
  { id: 14, question: "A transmission (window) defect characteristically:", options: ["Increases in size over the study", "Appears early, does not enlarge, and fades in late frames", "Leaks dye into the neurosensory retina", "Is brightest in the late phase"], correct: 1, explanation: "A window defect follows choroidal fluorescence: early appearance, peak with choroidal filling, no enlargement, and late fading as choroidal dye dilutes." },
  { id: 15, question: "Which pattern is characterized by decreasing brightness and unchanged size over time?", options: ["Leakage", "Pooling", "Staining", "Window (transmission) defect"], correct: 3, explanation: "The window defect dims in late frames (choroidal dye dilution) and never enlarges." },
  { id: 16, question: "Geographic atrophy exposing bare choroid through absent RPE produces which FA finding?", options: ["Leakage", "A transmission (window) defect", "Blocked fluorescence", "Pooling"], correct: 1, explanation: "Loss of RPE pigment unmasks normal choroidal fluorescence — an early window defect that fades late without leaking." },
  { id: 17, question: "The outer blood–retina barrier is formed by:", options: ["Retinal vascular endothelial tight junctions", "The retinal pigment epithelium", "Müller cell foot plates", "The internal limiting membrane"], correct: 1, explanation: "The RPE tight junctions form the outer BRB; the retinal endothelium forms the inner BRB." },
  { id: 18, question: "Cystoid macular edema from inner blood–retina barrier breakdown appears on FA as:", options: ["An early window defect", "Late petalloid pooling in the central macula with optic disc staining", "Blocked fluorescence", "Early bright staining of drusen"], correct: 1, explanation: "CME shows late petalloid pooling (Henle layer) and disc staining — classically Irvine–Gass after cataract surgery." },
  { id: 19, question: "On FA, \"classic\" choroidal neovascularization is characterized by:", options: ["A poorly defined area of late staining only", "An early, well-defined lacy hyperfluorescent network with progressive leakage", "Blocked fluorescence throughout the study", "An early window defect that fades late"], correct: 1, explanation: "Classic CNV is a discrete early network that leaks; occult CNV shows late, poorly defined leakage/staining." },
  { id: 20, question: "Drusen typically appear on FA as:", options: ["Early blocked fluorescence", "Staining — hyperfluorescence that increases then persists with fixed borders", "Progressive leakage with expanding borders", "Pooling under a detachment"], correct: 1, explanation: "Drusen stain: they take up and retain dye without leaking or expanding." },
  { id: 21, question: "The most common adverse effects of fluorescein injection are:", options: ["Anaphylaxis and shock", "Nausea/vomiting and urticaria, each in ~5%", "Seizures", "Permanent skin staining"], correct: 1, explanation: "Nausea/vomiting (~5%) and hives (~5%) are most common; nausea passes in seconds and hives respond to diphenhydramine." },
  { id: 22, question: "A patient's skin and urine turn yellow-green after FA. The appropriate action is:", options: ["Emergent evaluation for hepatic failure", "Reassurance — this is expected and resolves within hours", "Administer diphenhydramine", "Start IV corticosteroids"], correct: 1, explanation: "Skin/conjunctival yellowing (6–12 h) and discolored urine are universal, expected, and benign." },
  { id: 23, question: "The estimated risk of death from fluorescein angiography is approximately:", options: ["1:2,000", "1:22,000", "1:222,000", "1:2,000,000"], correct: 2, explanation: "Fatal reactions are rare, ~1:222,000; a physician and crash cart should nonetheless be available." },
  { id: 24, question: "A patient had urticaria after a prior fluorescein study and now needs another FA. The best approach is:", options: ["Refuse FA permanently", "Premedicate with antihistamines ± corticosteroids", "Use half the usual dye dose", "No precautions are needed"], correct: 1, explanation: "Prior urticaria increases recurrence risk; premedication with antihistamines and/or steroids reduces it." },
  { id: 25, question: "Painful extravasation of fluorescein into the skin during injection is managed with:", options: ["Warm compresses", "Ice-cold compresses for 5–10 minutes with close follow-up", "Incision and drainage", "Systemic antibiotics"], correct: 1, explanation: "Cold compresses and observation until swelling and pain resolve are recommended." },
  { id: 26, question: "Regarding FA in pregnancy and lactation:", options: ["It is absolutely contraindicated throughout pregnancy", "It is proven teratogenic", "It is often avoided in the first trimester (though no teratogenicity is proven) and the dye passes into breast milk", "It is completely safe with no considerations"], correct: 2, explanation: "No teratogenicity is proven, but many clinicians avoid the first trimester; fluorescein is excreted in breast milk." },
  { id: 27, question: "Indocyanine green is superior to fluorescein for imaging the choroid mainly because:", options: ["It is not protein-bound, so it diffuses freely", "It is ~98% protein-bound and near-infrared, so it stays intravascular and penetrates the RPE", "It is excreted renally", "It fluoresces in the ultraviolet range"], correct: 1, explanation: "High protein binding limits diffusion through choriocapillaris fenestrations, and near-infrared light penetrates pigment/blood — ideal for choroidal imaging." },
  { id: 28, question: "ICG excitation and emission peaks lie in which part of the spectrum?", options: ["Ultraviolet", "Blue-green", "Near-infrared (~790–835 nm)", "Red"], correct: 2, explanation: "ICG excitation ~790–805 nm and emission ~825–835 nm are both near-infrared." },
  { id: 29, question: "Indocyanine green is cleared by:", options: ["Renal excretion", "Hepatic metabolism and biliary excretion", "Exhalation", "RPE phagocytosis"], correct: 1, explanation: "ICG is metabolized by the liver and excreted into the bile." },
  { id: 30, question: "In the middle phase of a normal ICG angiogram (5–15 minutes), you expect:", options: ["First appearance of dye in the choroidal arteries", "Indistinct choroidal veins with diffuse homogeneous choroidal fluorescence and diminished retinal vessel fluorescence", "Complete absence of any fluorescence", "Bright leakage from the retinal capillaries"], correct: 1, explanation: "The middle phase shows fading choroidal vein detail with diffuse choroidal fluorescence and reduced retinal vessel signal." },
];

// ── Cornea · Mannis · Part 4 · Dry Eye & Ocular Allergy Medications
// Source: "Medication for Dry Eye and Ocular Allergy" (TFOS DEWS III–based lecture).
const CORNEA_MEDS_RECALL: RecallQ[] = [
  { id: 1, question: "What is the TFOS DEWS III definition of dry eye?", answer: "A multifactorial, symptomatic disease characterized by loss of homeostasis of the tear film and/or the ocular surface, in which tear film instability, hyperosmolarity, ocular surface inflammation and damage, and neurosensory abnormalities play etiological roles." },
  { id: 2, question: "What are the Step 1 (baseline / mild) interventions for dry eye?", answer: "Patient education and lifestyle modification, elimination of offending medications, low-viscosity lubrication, and lid hygiene with warm compresses for MGD." },
  { id: 3, question: "What defines Step 2 (moderate) dry eye management?", answer: "Advanced lubrication (preservative-free artificial tears, osmoprotectants, or hyaluronic acid), secretagogues, anti-inflammatory therapy, and doxycycline or azithromycin for chronic blepharitis/MGD." },
  { id: 4, question: "What are Steps 3 and 4 of dry eye management?", answer: "Step 3 (severe): biological substitutes (autologous serum/PRP) and mechanical interventions (punctal occlusion, contact lens, moisture chamber spectacles). Step 4 (refractory): surgery — tarsorrhaphy or amniotic membrane transplant." },
  { id: 5, question: "What is the trade-off of viscosity-enhancing artificial tears?", answer: "Higher viscosity increases tear residence/retention time and comfort, but causes transient blurring of vision and unwanted debris on the eyelids." },
  { id: 6, question: "Which cellulose demulcent is notable for promoting epithelial healing?", answer: "Carboxymethylcellulose (CMC) — a high-molecular-weight cellulose derivative that can promote epithelial healing. Cellulose derivatives (CMC, HPMC, HMC) are the most widely used demulcents." },
  { id: 7, question: "What is the role of Dextran 70 in artificial tears?", answer: "A high-molecular-weight (70 kDa) polysaccharide that enhances demulcent quality when combined with another demulcent (e.g., 0.3% HPMC + 0.1% dextran 70)." },
  { id: 8, question: "How do cationic oil-in-water nanoemulsion tears improve retention?", answer: "The positively charged oil nanodroplets are electrostatically attracted to the negatively charged ocular surface mucin, improving spreading and retention time; they also replace the lipid layer (nanoemulsion droplet size 10–100 nm)." },
  { id: 9, question: "What is an emollient (ointment) tear, and when is it used?", answer: "An ointment of petroleum/lanolin/mineral oils with higher viscosity and longer residence than demulcents, but it causes blurry vision and eyelash drying. Used for severe dry eye, at night, and for exposure keratopathy." },
  { id: 10, question: "What are the key properties of hyaluronic acid, and its residence-time advantage?", answer: "A glycosaminoglycan (sodium hyaluronate) that is water-retaining and mucoadhesive, giving tear film stability and healing of epithelial defects. 0.2% HA has significantly longer ocular surface residence time than 0.3% HPMC or 1.4% PVA." },
  { id: 11, question: "What is normal tear osmolarity, and the rationale for hypo-osmolar drops?", answer: "Normal tear osmolarity is 296–308 mOsm/L; dry eye causes hyperosmolarity. Hypo-osmolar eye drops lower the elevated tear osmolarity back toward normal." },
  { id: 12, question: "What are osmoprotectants and their effects?", answer: "Compounds (L-carnitine, erythritol, betaine, trehalose, glycerol) that protect cells under osmotic stress by balancing osmotic pressure without disturbing cell metabolism. They decrease apoptosis and inflammatory cytokines, increase goblet cells, and reduce corneal staining." },
  { id: 13, question: "Name the two classes of eye-drop preservatives with examples and relative toxicity.", answer: "Detergents (disrupt microbial cell membranes; high ocular toxicity) — benzalkonium chloride (BAK), Polyquad, cetrimide. Oxidizing agents (disrupt microbial metabolism; gentle on human tissue) — sodium perborate (Genaqua) and stabilized oxychloro complex (SOC/Purite)." },
  { id: 14, question: "What is the usage limit for preserved eye drops, and why?", answer: "Preserved drops should be used ≤4 times/day; using more than 4×/day for a long period causes preservative sensitivity/toxicity. Preservatives do help prevent contamination and can enhance corneal penetration of some drugs." },
  { id: 15, question: "Which electrolytes are most critical in artificial tears, and what are their roles?", answer: "Potassium (K) and bicarbonate (HCO3). K maintains corneal thickness; HCO3 supports mucin adhesion, promotes recovery, and helps regulate pH." },
  { id: 16, question: "Describe autologous serum eye drops — properties, required testing, and drawbacks.", answer: "Biologically similar to human tears (nutrients, pH, vitamins, fibronectin, growth factors); used at 20–100% concentration for severe ocular surface disease; serology (HIV, hepatitis, syphilis) is required. Benefits: epithelial healing, proliferation/migration, inhibition of inflammatory cytokines, increased goblet cells/mucin. Drawbacks: must be refrigerated, blood-borne infection and bacterial contamination risk, expensive, limited availability." },
  { id: 17, question: "How are secretagogues classified?", answer: "Oral: cholinergic agonists (pilocarpine, carbachol, bethanechol) and mucolytics (bromhexine, ambroxol). Topical: P2Y2 receptor agonist (diquafosol). They also reduce ocular surface inflammation." },
  { id: 18, question: "Oral pilocarpine — indication, dose, side effects, contraindications; and topical pilocarpine?", answer: "Indication: xerostomia (radiation-induced) and Sjögren syndrome; 5 mg orally qid. Side effects: excessive sweating, N/V, headache. Contraindicated in COPD, severe kidney disease, and heart disease. Topical pilocarpine has NO secretagogue effect." },
  { id: 19, question: "What is the mechanism and onset of diquafosol?", answer: "A P2Y2 purinergic receptor agonist that stimulates both water and mucin secretion; it takes about 2–4 weeks to see an effect (dosed roughly 6 times/day)." },
  { id: 20, question: "How does rebamipide work?", answer: "It promotes production of mucin-like glycoproteins (MUC1, MUC4, MUC16). Given as 2% QID; approved in Japan." },
  { id: 21, question: "Compare the mechanisms of cyclosporine A and lifitegrast in dry eye.", answer: "Cyclosporine A inhibits IL-2–driven T-lymphocyte activation (a calcineurin inhibitor), formulated as an oil-based emulsion (0.05% bid / 0.1% OD). Lifitegrast (5% bid) blocks the LFA-1/ICAM-1 interaction to inhibit T-cell migration (ICAM-1 is overexpressed on cornea/conjunctiva in dry eye)." },
  { id: 22, question: "How is doxycycline used in MGD, and what is its dual mechanism?", answer: "Doxycycline 100 mg bid for 1–2 weeks, then taper to 50 mg daily. Antibacterial effect decreases bacterial lipolytic enzymes; anti-inflammatory effect inhibits collagenase, phospholipase A2, and MMPs. Side effects: GI upset, photosensitization, azotemia. Contraindicated in pregnancy, breastfeeding, and allergy." },
  { id: 23, question: "Classify ocular allergy by hypersensitivity type.", answer: "Type I (IgE-mediated mast cell degranulation): acute allergic conjunctivitis, seasonal (SAC) and perennial (PAC) allergic conjunctivitis. Type IV (T-cell–mediated, delayed): vernal (VKC) and atopic (AKC) keratoconjunctivitis." },
  { id: 24, question: "What are the roles of H1 and H2 receptors in the early allergic response?", answer: "H1: increases vascular permeability → itching, pain, tearing, redness, and edema. H2: vasodilation, cell proliferation, and mucous production." },
  { id: 25, question: "What is the mechanism of mast cell stabilizers, and its clinical implication?", answer: "They block calcium influx into mast cells, preventing degranulation. Onset is delayed (~2 weeks), so they are used for prevention rather than acute relief (e.g., lodoxamide, pemirolast, cromolyn)." },
  { id: 26, question: "How do corticosteroids act in the arachidonic acid pathway, and how does that differ from NSAIDs?", answer: "Steroids inhibit phospholipase A2, blocking release of arachidonic acid and thereby suppressing BOTH the cyclooxygenase (prostaglandins) and lipoxygenase (leukotrienes) pathways. NSAIDs inhibit only cyclooxygenase. Steroids have no effect on mast cell/histamine release, but are the most potent agents for severe ocular allergy (short course ~2 weeks, effective in acute and chronic disease)." },
  { id: 27, question: "Which topical steroids have LOW versus HIGH IOP-raising potential?", answer: "Low potential: fluorometholone (FML) and loteprednol (an ester/'soft' steroid). High potential: 0.1% dexamethasone raises IOP the most; 1% prednisolone acetate (Pred Forte) is a potent anti-inflammatory. Loteprednol and FML are preferred when prolonged use is needed." },
  { id: 28, question: "List the ocular and systemic side effects of corticosteroids.", answer: "Ocular: ocular hypertension/glaucoma, posterior subcapsular cataract (PSC), secondary infection, poor epithelial healing, corneal thinning, uveitis, ptosis, and ocular discomfort. Systemic: adrenal insufficiency, Cushing syndrome, peptic ulcer, osteoporosis, hypertension/diabetes, muscle weakness/atrophy, activation of infection, and delayed wound healing." },
  { id: 29, question: "Compare the immunomodulators cyclosporine and tacrolimus — class, source, mechanism, and potency.", answer: "Both are calcineurin inhibitors that block T-cell activation and cytokine production. Cyclosporine A is a metabolite of the fungus Tolypocladium inflatum and binds cyclophilin; tacrolimus (FK506) is a macrolide from Streptomyces tsukubaensis and binds FK-binding protein, with roughly 100× the inhibitory potency of cyclosporine." },
  { id: 30, question: "What is the clinical role, onset, and dosing of topical cyclosporine?", answer: "It is not used as primary therapy — it is reserved for patients not responding to steroids, steroid responders (IOP rise), or those with steroid complications. Onset is slow (1–4 weeks) and long-term use is needed. Dosing: 0.05% (Restasis) bid or 0.1% (Ikervis) OD; off-label for VKC/AKC; main side effect is burning on instillation. Caution in children and pregnancy." },
  { id: 31, question: "Describe the layers and key components of the normal tear film.", answer: "From anterior to posterior: a lipid layer (from meibomian glands), a muco-aqueous layer (aqueous with dissolved gel-forming mucins plus proteins — lysozyme, lactoferrin, IgA, transferrin, galectin-3, trefoil factor), and the glycocalyx (membrane-spanning mucins) overlying the corneal/conjunctival epithelium." },
  { id: 32, question: "How do artificial tears differ compositionally from human tears?", answer: "Human tears contain aqueous, mucin, lipid, electrolytes, immunoglobulins, antimicrobial agents, and growth factors. Artificial tears replace the aqueous/mucin/lipid components with polymers and variable electrolytes, but LACK immunoglobulins, antimicrobial agents, and growth factors — and often add preservatives." },
  { id: 33, question: "What are the properties of an ideal artificial tear?", answer: "Physical characteristics similar to natural tears, a long ocular residence time, and preservative-free formulation." },
  { id: 34, question: "What are the properties of polyvinyl alcohol (PVA) tears?", answer: "PVA is a water-soluble polymer that increases contact/residence time, is transparent and colourless, and is non-irritating (related agents include polyvinyl pyrrolidone and polyvinyl chloride)." },
  { id: 35, question: "Define the oil-based emulsion droplet sizes used in artificial tears.", answer: "Macroemulsion: droplet > 100 nm (appears cloudy because droplets scatter light). Microemulsion: < 10 nm. Nanoemulsion: 10–100 nm. These emulsions replace the lipid layer (e.g., castor oil, mineral oil)." },
  { id: 36, question: "What is carbomer, and how does its retention compare?", answer: "Carbomer is high-molecular-weight polyacrylic acid. It has a longer retention time than other demulcents but shorter than petroleum-based ointments." },
  { id: 37, question: "What is the pH of natural tears, and what causes a stinging sensation on instillation?", answer: "Natural tear pH is 6.5–7.6 (varying with CO2 saturation and meibomian lipids in the tear film). Stinging results from a mismatch between the pH of the eye drop and the pH of the tears." },
  { id: 38, question: "What are the advantages of autologous serum eye drops?", answer: "They enhance corneal epithelial wound healing, increase epithelial cell proliferation and migration, inhibit release of inflammatory cytokines, and increase the number of goblet cells and mucin expression in the conjunctiva." },
  { id: 39, question: "How is bromhexine used as a secretagogue?", answer: "Bromhexine is an oral mucolytic secretagogue dosed at 24–48 mg/day divided tid; side effects include rash and nausea/vomiting." },
  { id: 40, question: "Compare the topical secretagogues diquafosol, rebamipide, and ecabet sodium.", answer: "Diquafosol increases BOTH aqueous and mucin (≈6 times/day, effect over 3–6 months). Rebamipide increases mucin (≈4 times/day, ~2 weeks). Ecabet sodium increases mucin (≈4 times/day, ~90 days)." },
  { id: 41, question: "How are macrolides (azithromycin) used in dry eye/MGD?", answer: "They have both antibacterial and anti-inflammatory effects and are used for MGD. Oral azithromycin (somewhat controversial) is pulsed 500 mg × 3 days weekly for 3 weeks (side effects: diarrhea, N/V); topical azithromycin is 1–1.5%." },
  { id: 42, question: "What surgical/mechanical options are used for dry eye?", answer: "Punctal occlusion (temporary or permanent), tarsorrhaphy, moisture chamber spectacles, and contact lenses." },
  { id: 43, question: "List the six categories of ocular allergy medication.", answer: "Antihistamines, vasoconstrictors, mast cell stabilizers, dual-acting drugs, steroids, and immunomodulators." },
  { id: 44, question: "Describe the early-phase allergic reaction sequence and its mediators.", answer: "Mast cell degranulation releases histamine (plus prostaglandins, tryptase, heparin). Nerve stimulation → itching (within 3–5 min); vasodilation → redness (5–10 min); endothelial gaping with fluid leakage → swelling." },
  { id: 45, question: "Describe the late-phase allergic reaction.", answer: "Cytokine-driven influx of eosinophils, PMNs, basophils, and T-lymphocytes into the conjunctival mucosa, with increased ICAM/VCAM expression. Eosinophil activation causes cellular disaggregation, epithelial desquamation, and tissue damage — a T-cell–mediated reaction." },
  { id: 46, question: "What are the non-pharmacologic treatments for ocular allergy?", answer: "Identify and avoid the allergen, avoid eye rubbing, remove causative agents (contact lens, sutures), saline (NSS) irrigation, protective eyeglasses, cold compresses, and air conditioning." },
  { id: 47, question: "Match each anti-allergy drug class to its main effect.", answer: "Artificial tears — dilute allergens/mediators; antihistamines & vasoconstrictors — block mediators; mast cell stabilizers — prevent mediator release; steroids & NSAIDs — inhibit arachidonic acid breakdown; immunomodulators — anti-inflammatory." },
  { id: 48, question: "What are the properties of topical antihistamines, with examples?", answer: "Selective H1 antagonists with rapid onset but short duration (3–4 hours); often combined with a vasoconstrictor for an additive effect. Examples: levocabastine (Livostin) 0.05% QID (caution < 12 yr) and emedastine (Emadine) 0.05% QID (caution < 3 yr and with contact lens use)." },
  { id: 49, question: "What is the mechanism, side-effect profile, and cautions of topical vasoconstrictors?", answer: "Adrenergic agonists that constrict conjunctival vessels (phenylephrine, tetrahydrozoline, naphazoline). Side effects: stinging, pupil dilation, blurred vision, epithelial erosion, and rebound congestion. Caution in cardiovascular disease and angle-closure glaucoma." },
  { id: 50, question: "What are combined antihistamine/vasoconstrictor eye drops?", answer: "Fixed combinations of an antihistamine (antazoline or pheniramine) with a decongestant (naphazoline or tetrahydrozoline) — e.g., Hista-oph, Spersallerg, Naphcon-A, Visine-A. Used for allergic conjunctivitis (off-label VKC/AKC). Side effects: burning, rebound congestion, headache, tachycardia. Caution in angle closure and with MAO inhibitors." },
  { id: 51, question: "Name mast cell stabilizer eye drops and their main use.", answer: "Lodoxamide (Alomide 0.1%), pemirolast (Pemirox 0.1%), and cromolyn sodium (Crolom 4%, Vividrin 2%). Primary use is vernal keratoconjunctivitis (VKC), off-label for allergic conjunctivitis, AKC, and GPC." },
  { id: 52, question: "What are the dual-acting (multiple-action) anti-allergy agents?", answer: "Agents that block histamine (H1) AND stabilize mast cells (some also inhibit eosinophils): alcaftadine (Lastacaft), olopatadine (Pataday 0.2% OD / Patanol 0.1% bid), ketotifen (Zaditen), epinastine (Elestat), and azelastine (Optivar)." },
  { id: 53, question: "What are the main topical corticosteroid molecules and preparations?", answer: "Prednisolone acetate (Pred Forte 1%, Pred Mild 0.125%) and prednisolone phosphate (Inflamase); dexamethasone (Maxidex 0.1%); fluorometholone (FML 0.1%, FML Forte 0.25%); and loteprednol etabonate (Lotemax 0.5%, Alrex 0.2%). Acetate/alcohol suspensions penetrate the cornea better than phosphate solutions." },
  { id: 54, question: "Give examples of combined steroid + antibiotic eye drops.", answer: "Tobradex (0.1% dexamethasone + 0.3% tobramycin), Zylet (0.5% loteprednol + 0.3% tobramycin), Maxitrol (dexamethasone + neomycin + polymyxin B), and Vigadexa (dexamethasone + moxifloxacin) — used for inflammatory conditions and after surgery." },
  { id: 55, question: "Name the ophthalmic NSAIDs and their uses.", answer: "Ketorolac (Acular 0.5%), nepafenac (Nevanac 0.1%), diclofenac (Voltaren), bromfenac (Xibrom), flurbiprofen (Ocufen), and indomethacin. They inhibit cyclooxygenase and are used for post-operative pain/inflammation and cystoid macular edema." },
  { id: 56, question: "What are the goals of ocular allergy treatment?", answer: "Relieve signs and symptoms promptly and effectively with minimal side effects; prevent further exacerbation and allow symptom-free living with the least drug use; and prevent serious complications of the disease." },
];

const CORNEA_MEDS_MCQ: MCQ[] = [
  { id: 1, question: "TFOS DEWS III lists all of the following as etiological in dry eye EXCEPT:", options: ["Tear film instability", "Hyperosmolarity", "Elevated intraocular pressure", "Neurosensory abnormalities"], correct: 2, explanation: "The DEWS III definition names tear film instability, hyperosmolarity, ocular surface inflammation/damage, and neurosensory abnormalities — not IOP." },
  { id: 2, question: "Which is a Step 1 (baseline) intervention for dry eye?", options: ["Autologous serum eye drops", "Punctal occlusion", "Low-viscosity lubrication and lid hygiene", "Amniotic membrane transplant"], correct: 2, explanation: "Step 1 is education/lifestyle, stopping offending meds, low-viscosity lubrication, and lid hygiene/warm compresses. The others are later steps." },
  { id: 3, question: "The main drawback of high-viscosity artificial tears is:", options: ["Corneal toxicity", "Transient blurring and debris on the eyelids", "Raised intraocular pressure", "Pupillary dilation"], correct: 1, explanation: "Higher viscosity improves retention but transiently blurs vision and can leave debris on the lids." },
  { id: 4, question: "Which demulcent is noted for promoting corneal epithelial healing?", options: ["Polyvinyl alcohol", "Carboxymethylcellulose (CMC)", "Dextran 70", "Propylene glycol"], correct: 1, explanation: "CMC is a high-molecular-weight cellulose derivative that can promote epithelial healing." },
  { id: 5, question: "Cationic oil-in-water nanoemulsion tears improve retention because:", options: ["Negatively charged droplets bind the cornea", "Positively charged oil droplets are attracted to negatively charged surface mucin", "They increase tear osmolarity", "They lower tear pH"], correct: 1, explanation: "Electrostatic attraction between the positively charged oil nanodroplets and negatively charged ocular surface mucin improves spreading and retention." },
  { id: 6, question: "An ointment (emollient) tear is most appropriate:", options: ["As daytime first-line for mild dry eye", "At night or for exposure keratopathy", "Immediately before driving", "For daytime use in contact lens wearers"], correct: 1, explanation: "Ointments blur vision, so they are used at night, for severe dry eye, and for exposure keratopathy." },
  { id: 7, question: "Compared with 0.3% HPMC or 1.4% PVA, 0.2% hyaluronic acid has:", options: ["Shorter residence time", "Significantly longer ocular surface residence time", "Higher preservative content", "No mucoadhesive property"], correct: 1, explanation: "0.2% HA has significantly longer ocular surface residence time than 0.3% HPMC or 1.4% PVA." },
  { id: 8, question: "Normal tear film osmolarity is approximately:", options: ["150–200 mOsm/L", "296–308 mOsm/L", "400–450 mOsm/L", "500 mOsm/L"], correct: 1, explanation: "Normal tear osmolarity is 296–308 mOsm/L; dry eye produces hyperosmolarity." },
  { id: 9, question: "Osmoprotectants (e.g., trehalose, betaine, L-carnitine) act by:", options: ["Raising tear osmolarity", "Protecting cells from osmotic stress without disturbing metabolism", "Blocking histamine", "Constricting conjunctival vessels"], correct: 1, explanation: "Osmoprotectants balance osmotic pressure without disturbing cell metabolism, reducing apoptosis, inflammatory cytokines, and corneal staining." },
  { id: 10, question: "Which preservative is a detergent-type with high ocular surface toxicity?", options: ["Sodium perborate", "Stabilized oxychloro complex (Purite)", "Benzalkonium chloride (BAK)", "Genaqua"], correct: 2, explanation: "BAK is a detergent preservative with high ocular toxicity; sodium perborate and SOC/Purite are gentler oxidizing agents." },
  { id: 11, question: "Preserved eye drops should generally be limited to:", options: ["Once daily", "≤ 4 times per day", "Unlimited frequency", "Night-time use only"], correct: 1, explanation: "Preserved drops used >4×/day long-term cause preservative sensitivity/toxicity; ≤4×/day is advised, otherwise switch to preservative-free." },
  { id: 12, question: "Which electrolytes are considered most critical in artificial tears?", options: ["Na and Cl", "Ca and Mg", "K and HCO3", "Fe and Cu"], correct: 2, explanation: "K (maintains corneal thickness) and HCO3 (mucin adhesion, recovery, pH) are the most critical electrolytes in artificial tears." },
  { id: 13, question: "Before prescribing autologous serum eye drops, which is required?", options: ["IOP measurement only", "Serologic testing for HIV, hepatitis, and syphilis", "Corneal topography", "Genetic testing"], correct: 1, explanation: "Blood-derived products require serology (HIV, hepatitis, syphilis) before preparation." },
  { id: 14, question: "Which statement about topical pilocarpine is correct?", options: ["It is the most effective topical secretagogue", "It has no secretagogue effect", "It stimulates P2Y2 receptors", "It is first-line for MGD"], correct: 1, explanation: "Only oral cholinergic agonists act as secretagogues; topical pilocarpine has no secretagogue effect." },
  { id: 15, question: "Oral pilocarpine is contraindicated in:", options: ["Hypertension only", "COPD, severe kidney disease, and heart disease", "Diabetes mellitus", "Migraine"], correct: 1, explanation: "Cholinergic stimulation is dangerous in COPD, severe renal disease, and heart disease." },
  { id: 16, question: "Diquafosol relieves dry eye by:", options: ["Blocking IL-2", "Stimulating the P2Y2 receptor to increase water and mucin secretion", "Inhibiting MMPs", "Constricting conjunctival vessels"], correct: 1, explanation: "Diquafosol is a P2Y2 purinergic agonist increasing aqueous and mucin secretion (effect in ~2–4 weeks)." },
  { id: 17, question: "Rebamipide improves the tear film by:", options: ["Reducing goblet cells", "Promoting mucin-like glycoproteins (MUC1, MUC4, MUC16)", "Blocking H1 receptors", "Raising tear osmolarity"], correct: 1, explanation: "Rebamipide up-regulates mucin-like glycoproteins (MUC1/4/16), improving the mucin layer." },
  { id: 18, question: "Lifitegrast reduces ocular surface inflammation by:", options: ["Blocking the LFA-1/ICAM-1 interaction to inhibit T-cell migration", "Stabilizing mast cells", "Antagonizing H1 receptors", "Inhibiting cyclooxygenase"], correct: 0, explanation: "Lifitegrast binds LFA-1 and blocks LFA-1/ICAM-1 binding; ICAM-1 is overexpressed on the ocular surface in dry eye." },
  { id: 19, question: "Doxycycline benefits MGD partly because it:", options: ["Increases bacterial lipase activity", "Inhibits collagenase, phospholipase A2, and MMPs", "Stimulates tear secretion via P2Y2", "Constricts conjunctival vessels"], correct: 1, explanation: "Beyond its antibacterial effect (reducing lipolytic enzymes), doxycycline inhibits collagenase, phospholipase A2, and MMPs." },
  { id: 20, question: "Doxycycline for MGD is contraindicated in:", options: ["Elderly patients", "Pregnancy and breastfeeding", "Diabetics", "Contact lens wearers"], correct: 1, explanation: "Tetracyclines are contraindicated in pregnancy and breastfeeding (and drug allergy)." },
  { id: 21, question: "Seasonal and perennial allergic conjunctivitis are mediated by:", options: ["Type IV (T-cell) delayed hypersensitivity", "Type I (IgE-mediated) hypersensitivity", "Type II cytotoxic reaction", "Type III immune-complex reaction"], correct: 1, explanation: "SAC and PAC are Type I, IgE-mediated mast cell degranulation. VKC and AKC involve Type IV." },
  { id: 22, question: "Vernal and atopic keratoconjunctivitis primarily involve:", options: ["Type I IgE-mediated degranulation only", "Type IV T-cell–mediated delayed hypersensitivity", "Complement-mediated cell lysis", "Neutrophilic vasculitis"], correct: 1, explanation: "VKC and AKC are chronic, T-cell–mediated (Type IV) forms of ocular allergy." },
  { id: 23, question: "Histamine acting on H1 receptors in the eye causes:", options: ["Vasoconstriction", "Increased vascular permeability → itching, redness, tearing, edema", "Suppression of mucous production", "Pupillary constriction"], correct: 1, explanation: "H1 stimulation raises vascular permeability, producing itching, redness, tearing, and edema; H2 causes vasodilation and mucous production." },
  { id: 24, question: "A key limitation of topical antihistamine eye drops (levocabastine, emedastine) is:", options: ["Slow onset over weeks", "Short duration of action (~3–4 hours)", "Raised intraocular pressure", "They stabilize mast cells only"], correct: 1, explanation: "Topical antihistamines act fast but only last ~3–4 hours, so they are often combined with a vasoconstrictor." },
  { id: 25, question: "A common problem with topical vasoconstrictor (decongestant) eye drops is:", options: ["Rebound congestion with chronic use", "Delayed onset over weeks", "Mast cell stabilization", "Lowering of IOP"], correct: 0, explanation: "Adrenergic vasoconstrictors cause rebound congestion; cautions include cardiovascular disease and angle-closure glaucoma." },
  { id: 26, question: "Mast cell stabilizers are best used:", options: ["For immediate relief of acute itching", "For prevention, because onset is delayed ~2 weeks", "As monotherapy for anaphylaxis", "To constrict conjunctival vessels"], correct: 1, explanation: "They block calcium influx and prevent degranulation, but the delayed (~2-week) onset makes them prophylactic agents." },
  { id: 27, question: "Olopatadine and ketotifen are examples of:", options: ["Pure vasoconstrictors", "Dual-acting antihistamine / mast cell stabilizers", "Calcineurin inhibitors", "NSAIDs"], correct: 1, explanation: "These multiple-action agents block H1 and stabilize mast cells (and affect eosinophils), giving both fast and sustained relief." },
  { id: 28, question: "How do corticosteroids differ from NSAIDs in the arachidonic acid pathway?", options: ["Steroids block only cyclooxygenase", "Steroids inhibit phospholipase A2 (upstream), blocking both COX and lipoxygenase; NSAIDs block only COX", "NSAIDs block phospholipase A2", "Both block only lipoxygenase"], correct: 1, explanation: "Steroids act upstream at phospholipase A2, suppressing both prostaglandins and leukotrienes; NSAIDs inhibit only COX." },
  { id: 29, question: "Which topical steroid has the LOWEST tendency to raise intraocular pressure?", options: ["0.1% Dexamethasone", "1% Prednisolone acetate", "Loteprednol or fluorometholone", "They all raise IOP equally"], correct: 2, explanation: "Loteprednol and fluorometholone have low IOP-raising potential; 0.1% dexamethasone raises IOP the most." },
  { id: 30, question: "Topical cyclosporine and tacrolimus share which mechanism/class?", options: ["Antihistamines", "Calcineurin inhibitors that block T-cell activation and cytokine production", "Mast cell stabilizers", "Adrenergic agonists"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both are calcineurin inhibitors; tacrolimus (binds FK-binding protein) is roughly 100× more potent than cyclosporine (binds cyclophilin)." },
  { id: 31, question: "In artificial tears, Dextran 70 is best described as:", options: ["A low-molecular-weight electrolyte", "A 70-kDa high-molecular-weight polysaccharide that enhances demulcent quality when combined with another demulcent", "A detergent preservative", "A cationic oil"], correct: 1, explanation: "Dextran 70 is a 70-kDa polysaccharide used with another demulcent (e.g., 0.3% HPMC + 0.1% dextran 70)." },
  { id: 32, question: "Liquid polyol demulcents (propylene glycol, PEG, glycerin) characteristically:", options: ["Have higher viscosity than cellulose", "Mimic mucin/glycocalyx adhesion but have lower viscosity than cellulose", "Are oil-based emulsions", "Contain benzalkonium chloride"], correct: 1, explanation: "Polyols are sugar-like hydrogenated carbohydrates that mimic mucin adhesion; their viscosity is lower than cellulose derivatives." },
  { id: 33, question: "A macroemulsion artificial tear (droplet > 100 nm) appears:", options: ["Perfectly clear", "Cloudy, because the droplets scatter light", "Bright yellow", "Effervescent"], correct: 1, explanation: "Larger droplets scatter light and look cloudy; nanoemulsions (10–100 nm) and microemulsions (<10 nm) are clearer." },
  { id: 34, question: "Carbomer is chemically:", options: ["A cellulose derivative", "Polyacrylic acid (high molecular weight) with retention longer than demulcents but less than petroleum", "A polysaccharide like dextran", "An oil"], correct: 1, explanation: "Carbomer is high-MW polyacrylic acid; its retention time is between demulcents and petroleum ointments." },
  { id: 35, question: "Compared with demulcents, emollient ointments have:", options: ["Lower viscosity", "Higher viscosity, giving longer residence but blurring vision and drying the lashes", "Identical properties to saline", "An osmotic mechanism"], correct: 1, explanation: "Petroleum/lanolin/mineral-oil ointments are more viscous and longer-lasting than demulcents but blur vision — hence night-time/severe use." },
  { id: 36, question: "Natural tear film pH is approximately:", options: ["5.0–5.5", "6.5–7.6", "8.0–8.5", "4.5"], correct: 1, explanation: "Tear pH is ~6.5–7.6; a mismatch between drop pH and tear pH causes a stinging sensation." },
  { id: 37, question: "Oxidizing-type preservatives (sodium perborate, stabilized oxychloro complex) are preferred because they:", options: ["Have high ocular toxicity", "Are gentle on human tissue, breaking down into water, oxygen, and salts", "Are strong detergents", "Cannot prevent contamination"], correct: 1, explanation: "Oxidizing agents disrupt microbial metabolism but degrade to innocuous products (e.g., sodium perborate → O2 + H2O), making them gentle." },
  { id: 38, question: "Autologous serum eye drops for severe ocular surface disease are typically used at what concentration?", options: ["1–5%", "20–100%", "0.1%", "200%"], correct: 1, explanation: "Serum is diluted to 20–100% and is biologically similar to human tears (nutrients, fibronectin, growth factors)." },
  { id: 39, question: "A recognized disadvantage of autologous serum eye drops is:", options: ["They must be refrigerated and carry blood-borne infection / contamination risk", "They contain no growth factors", "They reliably raise IOP", "They contain benzalkonium chloride"], correct: 0, explanation: "Serum drops need refrigeration, risk blood-borne infection and bacterial contamination, are expensive, and have limited availability." },
  { id: 40, question: "Which oral secretagogue is a mucolytic rather than a cholinergic agonist?", options: ["Pilocarpine", "Carbachol", "Bromhexine", "Bethanechol"], correct: 2, explanation: "Bromhexine (and ambroxol) are mucolytic oral secretagogues; pilocarpine, carbachol, and bethanechol are cholinergic agonists." },
  { id: 41, question: "Typical side effects of oral pilocarpine include:", options: ["Excessive sweating, nausea/vomiting, and headache", "Constipation and dry mouth", "Hypertension and mydriasis", "Photosensitivity"], correct: 0, explanation: "As a cholinergic agonist, pilocarpine causes sweating, GI upset, and headache; it is contraindicated in COPD, severe renal disease, and heart disease." },
  { id: 42, question: "Rebamipide ophthalmic suspension is dosed and licensed as:", options: ["2% QID, approved in Japan", "5% twice daily, US-approved", "An oral tablet only", "A once-yearly injection"], correct: 0, explanation: "Rebamipide (Mucosta) 2% QID, approved in Japan, up-regulates MUC1/4/16 mucin-like glycoproteins." },
  { id: 43, question: "Cyclosporine A for dry eye is formulated as:", options: ["An aqueous solution", "An oil-based emulsion", "A petroleum ointment", "A carbomer gel"], correct: 1, explanation: "Cyclosporine is an oil-based emulsion (0.05% bid / 0.1% OD) that inhibits IL-2–driven T-cell activation." },
  { id: 44, question: "A recognized side effect of lifitegrast is:", options: ["Raised intraocular pressure", "Decreased visual acuity and irritation", "Posterior subcapsular cataract", "Mydriasis"], correct: 1, explanation: "Lifitegrast commonly causes transient decreased VA and irritation/dysgeusia — not IOP rise or cataract." },
  { id: 45, question: "Oral azithromycin for MGD is often given as:", options: ["A single 1 g dose", "A pulse of 500 mg for 3 days, repeated weekly for 3 weeks", "100 mg daily for a year", "IV therapy only"], correct: 1, explanation: "A common (if debated) MGD regimen is pulsed oral azithromycin 500 mg × 3 days weekly × 3; topical azithromycin is 1–1.5%." },
  { id: 46, question: "Which is a mechanical/surgical option to retain tears in dry eye?", options: ["Punctal occlusion", "LASIK", "Trabeculectomy", "Vitrectomy"], correct: 0, explanation: "Punctal occlusion (temporary or permanent) retains tears; tarsorrhaphy, moisture chamber spectacles, and contact lenses are other options." },
  { id: 47, question: "In the early allergic response, itching from nerve stimulation appears within about:", options: ["3–5 minutes", "1 hour", "24 hours", "1 week"], correct: 0, explanation: "Histamine-driven nerve stimulation causes itching within ~3–5 minutes; vasodilation/redness follows at ~5–10 minutes." },
  { id: 48, question: "The late-phase allergic reaction is characterized by:", options: ["Immediate mast cell degranulation only", "Influx of eosinophils, neutrophils, basophils, and T-lymphocytes with increased ICAM/VCAM expression", "Vasoconstriction and pallor", "Absence of inflammation"], correct: 1, explanation: "The late phase recruits inflammatory cells to the conjunctival mucosa with adhesion-molecule upregulation and eosinophil-mediated tissue damage." },
  { id: 49, question: "In the anti-allergy scheme, mast cell stabilizers act to:", options: ["Block histamine receptors", "Prevent mediator release", "Constrict conjunctival vessels", "Dilute allergens"], correct: 1, explanation: "Mast cell stabilizers prevent mediator (e.g., histamine) release; antihistamines/vasoconstrictors block mediators; artificial tears dilute them." },
  { id: 50, question: "Topical antihistamine levocabastine (Livostin) carries an age caution in children under:", options: ["12 years", "6 months", "18 years", "No age caution exists"], correct: 0, explanation: "Levocabastine is cautioned in children <12 years; emedastine (Emadine) is cautioned <3 years and with contact lens use." },
  { id: 51, question: "The mechanism of topical vasoconstrictor (decongestant) drops in allergy is:", options: ["H1-receptor antagonism", "Adrenergic agonism causing conjunctival vessel constriction", "Mast cell stabilization", "Calcineurin inhibition"], correct: 1, explanation: "Vasoconstrictors are adrenergic agonists; side effects include mydriasis, epithelial erosion, and rebound congestion." },
  { id: 52, question: "Combined antihistamine/vasoconstrictor eye drops are specifically cautioned in patients taking:", options: ["Monoamine oxidase inhibitors (also caution in angle-closure)", "Vitamin C", "Oral antibiotics", "Statins"], correct: 0, explanation: "The decongestant component interacts with MAO inhibitors and can precipitate angle closure." },
  { id: 53, question: "Which drug is a mast cell stabilizer commonly used in vernal keratoconjunctivitis?", options: ["Olopatadine", "Cromolyn sodium (or lodoxamide / pemirolast)", "Naphazoline", "Prednisolone acetate"], correct: 1, explanation: "Cromolyn, lodoxamide (Alomide), and pemirolast (Pemirox) are mast cell stabilizers used in VKC (olopatadine is dual-acting)." },
  { id: 54, question: "Olopatadine 0.2% (Pataday) dosing is:", options: ["Once daily (OD)", "Every hour", "Once weekly", "Six times daily"], correct: 0, explanation: "Pataday (olopatadine 0.2%) is once daily; Patanol (olopatadine 0.1%) is twice daily." },
  { id: 55, question: "Which topical steroid preparation tends to raise intraocular pressure the MOST?", options: ["Fluorometholone", "Loteprednol", "0.1% dexamethasone", "Prednisolone 0.125%"], correct: 2, explanation: "0.1% dexamethasone has the greatest IOP-raising potential; fluorometholone and loteprednol have low potential." },
  { id: 56, question: "Tobradex is a fixed combination of:", options: ["Loteprednol + tobramycin", "Dexamethasone + tobramycin", "Dexamethasone + neomycin + polymyxin B", "Prednisolone + ofloxacin"], correct: 1, explanation: "Tobradex = 0.1% dexamethasone + 0.3% tobramycin. (Zylet = loteprednol + tobramycin; Maxitrol = dexamethasone + neomycin + polymyxin B.)" },
  { id: 57, question: "Ophthalmic NSAIDs (e.g., ketorolac, nepafenac) act by:", options: ["Inhibiting phospholipase A2", "Inhibiting only cyclooxygenase", "Stabilizing mast cells", "Blocking H1 receptors"], correct: 1, explanation: "NSAIDs inhibit only COX (unlike steroids, which act upstream at phospholipase A2); used for post-op pain/inflammation and CME." },
  { id: 58, question: "Tacrolimus differs from cyclosporine in that it:", options: ["Is a corticosteroid", "Binds FK-binding protein, is ~100× more potent, and is derived from Streptomyces tsukubaensis", "Blocks histamine receptors", "Has no immunosuppressive effect"], correct: 1, explanation: "Tacrolimus (FK506) binds FK-binding protein and is roughly 100× more potent than cyclosporine, which binds cyclophilin." },
  { id: 59, question: "Topical cyclosporine is best characterized as:", options: ["First-line primary therapy for all dry eye", "Not a primary therapy — reserved for steroid non-responders/responders/complications, with slow (1–4 week) onset", "A rapid-acting decongestant", "A preservative"], correct: 1, explanation: "Cyclosporine is second-line, slow in onset (1–4 weeks), and needs long-term use; caution in children and pregnancy." },
  { id: 60, question: "Which correctly matches an anti-allergy drug class to its mechanism?", options: ["Steroid → mast cell stabilization", "Artificial tears → dilution of allergens and mediators", "Antihistamine → arachidonic acid inhibition", "Immunomodulator → vasoconstriction"], correct: 1, explanation: "Artificial tears dilute allergens/mediators; steroids/NSAIDs act on the arachidonic acid pathway; antihistamines block mediators; immunomodulators are anti-inflammatory." },
];

// ── Basic Science · BCSC Section 2 · Part 1 · Pharmacokinetics & Ocular Drug Delivery
// Source: BCSC Section 2 (Fundamentals & Principles), Ch. 15 (Pharmacologic Principles).
const BASIC_PK_RECALL: RecallQ[] = [
  { id: 1, question: "List the routes of ophthalmic drug delivery.", answer: "Topical (eyedrops), oral/systemic, intravitreal, intracameral, subconjunctival, sub-Tenon, retrobulbar, and posterior juxtascleral." },
  { id: 2, question: "Why is topical the most common route, and what is the primary intraocular pathway?", answer: "Topical eyedrops maximize anterior segment concentration while minimizing systemic toxicity. The transcorneal route is the primary pathway for a medication to reach intraocular concentrations." },
  { id: 3, question: "What is the topical bioavailability, and how much of an eyedrop is retained?", answer: "Topical bioavailability is < 5%. Of a 50-μL drop, the tear lake only rises from ~7 to ~10 μL, so at most ~20% is retained; ocular tissues ultimately absorb only 1–10% of the applied medication." },
  { id: 4, question: "Why is there no benefit to instilling two drops of the same drug at once?", answer: "The tear lake holds only ~10 μL, so a second immediate drop mostly overflows and washes out the first. Patients should wait at least 5 minutes between drops." },
  { id: 5, question: "What is the tear turnover rate, and how quickly is drug lost?", answer: "Tear turnover is ~16%/minute (faster with reflex tearing). Only ~10% of the original dose remains at 4 minutes and ~3.4% at 10 minutes after instillation." },
  { id: 6, question: "Define the residence time of a topical medication.", answer: "The amount of time a drug remains in the tear reservoir and tear film. It is affected by drug formulation, the timing of subsequent drops, tear production, and drainage." },
  { id: 7, question: "How do nasolacrimal occlusion and eyelid closure improve topical therapy?", answer: "Both block the nasolacrimal pump, increasing residence time and corneal absorption while decreasing systemic absorption and toxicity. Apply digital pressure at the medial canthus, or close the eyes for 5 minutes, after each drop." },
  { id: 8, question: "How does topical drug reach the systemic circulation, and what is the % → mg/mL trick?", answer: "Absorption across the nasal mucosa bypasses first-pass hepatic metabolism, so a drop can give a meaningful systemic dose. Concentration: add a zero to the percentage for mg/mL (1% = 10 mg/mL); there are ~20 drops per mL." },
  { id: 9, question: "How fast does the nasolacrimal system remove drug relative to ocular absorption?", answer: "The nasolacrimal system can remove topically applied medication about 100× faster than the ocular surface can absorb it." },
  { id: 10, question: "What factors determine corneal drug penetration?", answer: "Concentration/solubility in the vehicle, vehicle viscosity, lipid solubility, pH, ionic and steric form, molecular size, surfactants, reflex tearing, and drug binding." },
  { id: 11, question: "Distinguish a solution from a suspension, with examples.", answer: "A solution requires adequate aqueous solubility. A suspension disperses a poorly soluble drug in a medium — it must be shaken before use and may be more irritating. Examples of suspensions: prednisolone acetate and brinzolamide." },
  { id: 12, question: "What are the characteristics of an emulsion, with examples?", answer: "A mixture of two immiscible liquids stabilized by an emulsifier; it gives increased contact time and bioavailability, looks cloudy but needs no shaking, and is more viscous (foreign-body sensation). Examples: difluprednate and cyclosporine." },
  { id: 13, question: "State the key concentration conversions.", answer: "1% = 1 g/100 mL = 10 mg/mL. A 1:1000 dilution = 1 mg/mL = 0.1%." },
  { id: 14, question: "What is the role of viscosity agents, and the optimal viscosity?", answer: "Methylcellulose, PVA, and gellan/xanthan gum increase retention in the inferior cul-de-sac (allowing once-daily timolol). Optimal viscosity is ~12–15 cP; above 15 cP causes irritation, reflex blinking, stickiness, and blurring without more absorption." },
  { id: 15, question: "Describe the lipid-solubility barriers of the cornea.", answer: "The corneal epithelium (lipophilic) and endothelium (lipophilic) sandwich a hydrophilic stroma, so an ideal drug is amphipathic — but lipid solubility matters more than water solubility for penetration. Tight junctions and desmosomes limit paracellular passage." },
  { id: 16, question: "How does conjunctival permeability compare with the cornea?", answer: "The conjunctiva is ~20× more permeable to small water-soluble molecules than the cornea, because of its larger paracellular spaces — but rapid clearance limits its contribution to intraocular drug levels." },
  { id: 17, question: "How do pH and ionization affect penetration?", answer: "Nonionized (uncharged) molecules are more lipophilic and cross membranes more readily; raising the pH increases the uncharged fraction and thus penetration. Many ophthalmic drugs are alkaloids (weak bases), most stable at acidic pH. Tear pH is ~7.4." },
  { id: 18, question: "How does scleral charge affect drug passage?", answer: "The scleral extracellular matrix is negatively charged, which limits passage of positively charged molecules — even though the sclera itself is hydrophilic." },
  { id: 19, question: "How does molecular size influence penetration?", answer: "Small (< 450 Da) lipophilic molecules favor transcellular pathways; larger hydrophilic molecules favor paracellular pathways. Transscleral absorption depends more on molecular size than on lipophilicity." },
  { id: 20, question: "How do surfactant preservatives affect drug penetration?", answer: "Surface-active preservatives (e.g., benzalkonium chloride) disrupt corneal epithelial cell membranes, reducing the barrier and increasing penetration — 0.1% carbachol + 0.03% BAK gives the same miosis as 2% carbachol alone. Corneal abrasion similarly increases penetration." },
  { id: 21, question: "What triggers reflex tearing, and why does it matter?", answer: "Non-isotonic solutions, nonphysiologic pH, or irritants trigger reflex tearing that washes out the tear-lake drug reservoir and shortens corneal contact time." },
  { id: 22, question: "How does drug binding affect pharmacokinetics? Give an example.", answer: "Tear/ocular-surface proteins and melanin bind drugs, creating a slow-release reservoir or making drug unavailable — altering onset, peak, and duration, and sometimes causing toxicity after discontinuation. Example: chloroquine/hydroxychloroquine retinal toxicity that progresses even after the drug is stopped." },
  { id: 23, question: "What is the composition of ophthalmic ointments, and which drugs benefit?", answer: "Petrolatum + mineral oil (mineral oil lets it melt at body temperature). Water-soluble drugs sit as microcrystals with slow release. Fluorometholone, chloramphenicol, and tetracycline reach higher aqueous levels as an ointment than as drops." },
  { id: 24, question: "What barriers do periocular injections bypass, and what routes reach the posterior segment?", answer: "Subconjunctival/sub-Tenon injections bypass the conjunctival and corneal epithelial barriers. Drug can reach the posterior segment transsclerally into the uvea, via periocular vessels into the systemic circulation, or transcorneally into the anterior segment." },
  { id: 25, question: "What is the advantage of a sub-Tenon injection?", answer: "The Tenon capsule is a lipophilic barrier; a hydrophilic drug placed in the sub-Tenon space penetrates intraocular tissue faster than a topical application — useful for low-lipid-solubility drugs like penicillin, and for delivering anesthesia." },
  { id: 26, question: "What are retrobulbar/peribulbar and other local injections used for?", answer: "Retrobulbar/peribulbar injections act at the injection site (not intraocular) — mainly for anesthesia. Other local injectables include botulinum toxin (blepharospasm, hemifacial spasm, strabismus) and retrobulbar alcohol (chronic pain in blind eyes)." },
  { id: 27, question: "What are the two types of intraocular injection and their risks?", answer: "Intracameral (into the anterior chamber) and intravitreal (into the vitreous). Risks include transient ocular hypertension and inflammation/infection; preservative-free preparations and strict asepsis are essential." },
  { id: 28, question: "Which antibiotics are used intracamerally for endophthalmitis prophylaxis?", answer: "Given at the end of cataract surgery: cefuroxime (broad-spectrum cephalosporin), vancomycin (covers MRSA but risks resistance and hemorrhagic occlusive retinal vasculitis), or diluted preservative-free moxifloxacin (4th-generation fluoroquinolone). All must be preservative-free." },
  { id: 29, question: "Why must intracameral medications such as lidocaine be preservative-free?", answer: "Preservatives (or dosing errors) with intracameral medications can cause toxic anterior segment syndrome (TASS)." },
  { id: 30, question: "What are the main categories of intravitreally delivered drugs?", answer: "Anti-VEGF agents (CNV, diabetic retinopathy, DME, RVO), corticosteroids (triamcinolone; sustained-release dexamethasone and fluocinolone implants), antivirals (foscarnet, ganciclovir for CMV), and surgical adjuncts (silicone oil, intraocular gases, perfluorocarbon)." },
  { id: 31, question: "How are intravitreal drugs cleared, and how does that affect half-life?", answer: "Hydrophilic, high-molecular-weight drugs exit anteriorly via aqueous humor outflow (longer half-life); lipophilic, low-molecular-weight drugs exit posteriorly across the retina/RPE into the choroid (shorter half-life)." },
  { id: 32, question: "Describe the blood–ocular barriers to systemically administered drugs.", answer: "The retinal vascular endothelium is nonfenestrated with tight junctions (like the brain). The choroid and ciliary body have fenestrated vessels but are sequestered by the RPE tight junctions and the nonpigmented ciliary epithelium, respectively." },
  { id: 33, question: "What determines how well a systemic drug penetrates the eye?", answer: "Higher lipid solubility (chloramphenicol penetrates ~20× better than penicillin) and lower plasma-protein binding — only the unbound fraction crosses the barrier, so >90%-bound sulfonamides penetrate poorly. Bolus dosing exceeds protein binding, giving higher intraocular peaks than a slow drip." },
  { id: 34, question: "Which oral antifungals penetrate the eye well, and give a sustained-release oral example.", answer: "Fluconazole and voriconazole have high oral bioavailability and good intraocular levels (used for endogenous fungal endophthalmitis). Sustained-release acetazolamide extends IOP lowering from ~10 to ~20 hours." },
  { id: 35, question: "Why does an inflamed eye show better drug penetration?", answer: "Inflammation disrupts the blood–aqueous and blood–retina barriers (demonstrated by fluorescein leakage during angiography), increasing intraocular drug penetration compared with a healthy eye." },
  { id: 36, question: "What are prodrugs, and give ophthalmic examples.", answer: "Inactive derivatives activated by ocular enzymes (esterases/amidases), with improved lipid solubility/penetration. Prostaglandin analogues (latanoprost, travoprost, tafluprost) are hydrolyzed to active FP-receptor agonists; valacyclovir → acyclovir; famciclovir → penciclovir." },
  { id: 37, question: "What are ocular inserts, and how do soluble and insoluble types differ?", answer: "Sterile drug-impregnated devices placed in the conjunctival fornix for steady-state delivery. Soluble inserts dissolve via interaction with the tear film (no removal needed); insoluble inserts give more constant release but must be removed. The first was a pilocarpine insert (40 μg/hr, 1970s)." },
  { id: 38, question: "Describe intraocular sustained-release implants.", answer: "The first was the ganciclovir intravitreal implant for CMV retinitis (discontinued 2015). Current FDA-approved implants: fluocinolone acetonide intravitreal implants, a biodegradable 0.7-mg dexamethasone intravitreal implant, and a biodegradable 10-µg bimatoprost intracameral implant." },
  { id: 39, question: "Describe punctal-plug drug delivery.", answer: "The only FDA-approved system is a resorbable intracanalicular dexamethasone insert (0.4 mg over 30 days) for postoperative inflammation/pain. Advantages: no preservative exposure, lower dose, controlled release; limitations: low dose capacity, irritation, and spontaneous extrusion." },
  { id: 40, question: "Summarize liposomes, nanotechnology, and iontophoresis for ocular delivery.", answer: "Liposomes are phospholipid-bilayer microspheres (water-soluble drug in the aqueous core, hydrophobic drug in the bilayer; limited by short shelf life and low loading). Nanotechnology uses nanoparticles/micelles/emulsions (e.g., 0.09% cyclosporine nanomicelle for dry eye). Iontophoresis uses an electrical current to drive charged molecules into tissue for high local concentration (limited by discomfort/tissue damage)." },
  { id: 41, question: "Distinguish pharmacogenetics from pharmacogenomics.", answer: "Pharmacogenetics studies how variation in single genes affects drug efficacy/toxicity; pharmacogenomics considers many genes. It divides into variations affecting drug metabolism (pharmacokinetics) and drug targets (pharmacodynamics). Ophthalmic examples (AMD, glaucoma — e.g., PTGFR SNPs and latanoprost response) exist but are conflicting." },
  { id: 42, question: "How does aging alter drug pharmacokinetics?", answer: "Older patients have less lean body mass, less body water and albumin, and more adipose tissue, plus declining renal function and variable hepatic changes. These extend the half-life of most systemic drugs and potentiate effects, so drug effects and toxicity can increase even when the dose is reduced." },
];

const BASIC_PK_MCQ: MCQ[] = [
  { id: 1, question: "The primary pathway by which a topically applied medication reaches intraocular concentrations is the:", options: ["Transconjunctival route", "Transcorneal route", "Transscleral route", "Systemic circulation"], correct: 1, explanation: "The transcorneal route is the main pathway for topical drugs to achieve intraocular levels." },
  { id: 2, question: "At most, approximately what percentage of a topically instilled eyedrop is retained by the eye?", options: ["~20%", "~50%", "~80%", "~100%"], correct: 0, explanation: "The tear lake only rises from ~7 to ~10 μL, so at most ~20% of a 50-μL drop is retained." },
  { id: 3, question: "The tear lake of a blinking, upright eye holds about:", options: ["3 μL", "10 μL", "30 μL", "50 μL"], correct: 1, explanation: "The tear lake holds ~10 μL, which is why a second simultaneous drop overflows." },
  { id: 4, question: "Tear turnover in the undisturbed eye is approximately:", options: ["1%/min", "16%/min", "50%/min", "90%/min"], correct: 1, explanation: "Tear turnover is ~16%/min (faster with reflex tearing), rapidly clearing instilled drug." },
  { id: 5, question: "Which maneuver increases ocular drug residence time while decreasing systemic absorption?", options: ["Instilling two drops at once", "Nasolacrimal occlusion or 5-minute eyelid closure", "Blinking rapidly after instillation", "Using a less viscous vehicle"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both block the nasolacrimal pump, raising ocular absorption and lowering systemic absorption/toxicity." },
  { id: 6, question: "A 1% ophthalmic solution contains how much drug per mL?", options: ["1 mg/mL", "10 mg/mL", "100 mg/mL", "0.1 mg/mL"], correct: 1, explanation: "1% = 1 g/100 mL = 10 mg/mL (add a zero to the percentage)." },
  { id: 7, question: "A 1:1000 solution is equivalent to:", options: ["1%", "0.1%", "0.01%", "10%"], correct: 1, explanation: "1:1000 = 1 g/1000 mL = 1 mg/mL = 0.1%." },
  { id: 8, question: "Ocular tissues absorb approximately what fraction of a topically applied medication?", options: ["1–10%", "20–30%", "~50%", "~80%"], correct: 0, explanation: "Only about 1–10% of a topical drop is actually absorbed by ocular tissues." },
  { id: 9, question: "Topical drug absorbed via the nasal mucosa is clinically significant because it:", options: ["Undergoes extensive first-pass metabolism", "Bypasses first-pass hepatic metabolism, reaching meaningful blood levels", "Is immediately excreted", "Cannot enter the bloodstream"], correct: 1, explanation: "Nasal mucosal absorption avoids first-pass liver metabolism, so a drop or two can deliver a systemic dose." },
  { id: 10, question: "Prednisolone acetate and brinzolamide are examples of which formulation?", options: ["Solution", "Suspension", "Emulsion", "Ointment"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both are suspensions of poorly soluble drug — they must be shaken before use." },
  { id: 11, question: "Which ophthalmic formulation must be shaken before instillation?", options: ["Solution", "Suspension", "Emulsion", "Gel-forming drop"], correct: 1, explanation: "A suspension must be shaken to redistribute the drug; an emulsion does not require shaking." },
  { id: 12, question: "Difluprednate and cyclosporine are formulated as:", options: ["Suspensions", "Emulsions", "Solutions", "Ointments"], correct: 1, explanation: "Both are topical emulsions (two immiscible liquids with an emulsifier)." },
  { id: 13, question: "An advantage of an emulsion over a solution is:", options: ["It never blurs vision", "Increased contact time and bioavailability", "It requires shaking", "Lower viscosity"], correct: 1, explanation: "Emulsions increase contact time and bioavailability, though they are more viscous (FB sensation)." },
  { id: 14, question: "The optimal viscosity for an ophthalmic vehicle is about:", options: ["1–2 cP", "12–15 cP", "30–40 cP", "> 50 cP"], correct: 1, explanation: "Delivery improves in the 1–15 cP range, optimally 12–15 cP." },
  { id: 15, question: "Viscosity above 15 cP tends to:", options: ["Proportionally increase aqueous drug levels", "Cause irritation, reflex blinking, and blurring without added benefit", "Improve comfort", "Reduce drainage"], correct: 1, explanation: "Above 15 cP there is no proportional gain, and irritation, reflex blinking, stickiness, and blurring occur." },
  { id: 16, question: "The corneal stroma is best characterized as:", options: ["Lipophilic", "Hydrophilic", "Positively charged", "Impermeable"], correct: 1, explanation: "The stroma is hydrophilic, sandwiched between lipophilic epithelium and endothelium." },
  { id: 17, question: "To cross the cornea, an ideal drug should be:", options: ["Purely lipophilic", "Purely hydrophilic", "Amphipathic, with lipid solubility being more important", "Large and charged"], correct: 2, explanation: "The layered cornea favors amphipathic drugs, but lipid solubility is the more important determinant of penetration." },
  { id: 18, question: "Compared with the cornea, the conjunctiva is roughly how much more permeable to small water-soluble molecules?", options: ["Equal", "2×", "20×", "100×"], correct: 2, explanation: "The conjunctiva is ~20× more permeable to small water-soluble molecules due to larger paracellular spaces." },
  { id: 19, question: "Raising the pH of a weak-base drug solution generally:", options: ["Increases the ionized fraction and decreases penetration", "Increases the uncharged, lipid-soluble fraction and increases penetration", "Has no effect on penetration", "Precipitates the drug"], correct: 1, explanation: "A higher pH shifts a weak base toward the uncharged, more lipid-soluble form, improving penetration." },
  { id: 20, question: "The negatively charged scleral extracellular matrix preferentially limits passage of:", options: ["Negatively charged molecules", "Positively charged molecules", "Neutral molecules", "Lipophilic molecules"], correct: 1, explanation: "The negatively charged scleral matrix repels/retards positively charged molecules." },
  { id: 21, question: "For transcellular corneal penetration, molecules are best if they are:", options: ["Large and hydrophilic", "Small (< 450 Da) and lipophilic", "Highly charged", "Heavily protein-bound"], correct: 1, explanation: "Small (<450 Da) lipophilic molecules cross transcellularly; larger hydrophilic ones use paracellular routes." },
  { id: 22, question: "Transscleral absorption is limited more by:", options: ["Lipophilicity", "Molecular size", "pH", "Charge alone"], correct: 1, explanation: "Although the sclera is hydrophilic, transscleral passage depends more on molecular size than lipophilicity." },
  { id: 23, question: "Adding benzalkonium chloride to a drop increases penetration because it:", options: ["Raises the solution pH", "Disrupts corneal epithelial cell membranes, reducing the barrier", "Increases viscosity", "Binds ocular melanin"], correct: 1, explanation: "As a surfactant, BAK disrupts epithelial membranes and lowers the barrier (0.1% carbachol + 0.03% BAK ≈ 2% carbachol)." },
  { id: 24, question: "Retinal toxicity that progresses even after the drug is discontinued is characteristic of:", options: ["Timolol", "Chloroquine / hydroxychloroquine", "Latanoprost", "Acetazolamide"], correct: 1, explanation: "Melanin binding creates a reservoir, so aminoquinoline retinal toxicity can progress after stopping the drug." },
  { id: 25, question: "Ophthalmic ointments are typically composed of:", options: ["Water and glycerin", "Petrolatum and mineral oil", "Hyaluronic acid", "Balanced salt solution"], correct: 1, explanation: "Petrolatum + mineral oil (which melts at body temperature and is a lipid solvent)." },
  { id: 26, question: "Which drugs achieve higher aqueous levels as an ointment than as drops?", options: ["Timolol and pilocarpine", "Fluorometholone, chloramphenicol, and tetracycline", "Latanoprost", "Acetazolamide"], correct: 1, explanation: "These lipophilic-plus-somewhat-water-soluble drugs escape the ointment and reach higher aqueous levels." },
  { id: 27, question: "Sub-Tenon injection is especially useful for drugs that are:", options: ["Highly lipid-soluble", "Low in lipid solubility (e.g., penicillin)", "Gases", "Preserved"], correct: 1, explanation: "Placing a poorly lipid-soluble drug past the Tenon barrier lets it penetrate faster than topical application." },
  { id: 28, question: "Toxic anterior segment syndrome (TASS) after an intracameral medication is most associated with:", options: ["Preservatives or dosing errors", "Preservative-free lidocaine", "Balanced salt solution", "Trypan blue"], correct: 0, explanation: "Preservatives and/or dosing errors with intracameral agents cause TASS — use preservative-free preparations." },
  { id: 29, question: "The most common form of intraocular drug delivery is:", options: ["Intracameral injection", "Intravitreal injection", "Subconjunctival injection", "Retrobulbar injection"], correct: 1, explanation: "Intravitreal injection is the most common intraocular delivery route (anti-VEGF, steroids, etc.)." },
  { id: 30, question: "Intracameral cefuroxime given at the end of cataract surgery is used to:", options: ["Dilate the pupil", "Prevent endophthalmitis", "Stain the anterior capsule", "Lower intraocular pressure"], correct: 1, explanation: "Intracameral antibiotics (cefuroxime, moxifloxacin, vancomycin) reduce postoperative endophthalmitis." },
  { id: 31, question: "A rare but serious complication of intracameral vancomycin is:", options: ["TASS", "Hemorrhagic occlusive retinal vasculitis", "Cataract", "Angle-closure glaucoma"], correct: 1, explanation: "Vancomycin is linked to hemorrhagic occlusive retinal vasculitis (HORV), and its indiscriminate use risks resistance." },
  { id: 32, question: "Which intracameral agent is used to constrict the pupil during intraocular surgery?", options: ["Epinephrine", "Acetylcholine or carbachol", "Phenylephrine", "Tropicamide"], correct: 1, explanation: "Acetylcholine and carbachol are intracameral miotics; epinephrine/phenylephrine are used for dilation." },
  { id: 33, question: "Hydrophilic, high-molecular-weight intravitreal drugs are cleared mainly via:", options: ["The posterior (retina/RPE/choroid) route", "The anterior (aqueous outflow) route, giving a longer half-life", "Nasolacrimal drainage", "Corneal evaporation"], correct: 1, explanation: "Large hydrophilic molecules exit anteriorly with aqueous outflow, giving a longer half-life than posterior clearance." },
  { id: 34, question: "The retinal vascular endothelium resembles that of the brain because it is:", options: ["Fenestrated", "Nonfenestrated with tight junctions", "Absent", "Highly permeable"], correct: 1, explanation: "Retinal vessels are nonfenestrated with tight junctions, forming the inner blood–retina barrier." },
  { id: 35, question: "The fenestrated choroidal vessels are sequestered from the retina by:", options: ["The sclera", "The RPE tight junctions", "Bruch membrane alone", "The vitreous"], correct: 1, explanation: "The RPE tight junctions form the outer blood–retina barrier, sequestering the fenestrated choroid." },
  { id: 36, question: "Which fraction of a systemically administered drug can cross the blood–ocular barrier?", options: ["Protein-bound", "Unbound (free)", "Ionized", "Metabolized"], correct: 1, explanation: "Only the unbound (free) drug crosses; heavy protein binding limits penetration." },
  { id: 37, question: "Chloramphenicol penetrates the eye ~20× better than penicillin mainly because it is:", options: ["More protein-bound", "More lipid-soluble", "Smaller", "More charged"], correct: 1, explanation: "Higher lipid solubility improves blood–ocular barrier penetration." },
  { id: 38, question: "Sulfonamides penetrate the eye poorly despite being lipid-soluble because:", options: ["They are too small", "More than 90% is bound to plasma proteins", "They are highly ionized", "They are metabolized within the eye"], correct: 1, explanation: "Only free drug crosses; >90% protein binding leaves little available to penetrate." },
  { id: 39, question: "Bolus IV administration achieves higher intraocular levels than a slow drip because it:", options: ["Avoids renal clearance", "Exceeds the plasma protein–binding capacity, raising free drug", "Is more lipid-soluble", "Bypasses the liver"], correct: 1, explanation: "A bolus saturates protein binding, transiently increasing free drug and intraocular peaks." },
  { id: 40, question: "Which oral antifungals achieve good intraocular concentrations for endogenous fungal endophthalmitis?", options: ["Amphotericin and nystatin", "Fluconazole and voriconazole", "Griseofulvin", "Terbinafine"], correct: 1, explanation: "Fluconazole and voriconazole have high oral bioavailability and good intraocular penetration." },
  { id: 41, question: "Drug penetration into an inflamed eye is typically:", options: ["Decreased", "Increased, due to blood–ocular barrier disruption", "Unchanged", "Completely blocked"], correct: 1, explanation: "Inflammation breaks down the blood–aqueous and blood–retina barriers, increasing penetration." },
  { id: 42, question: "Latanoprost, travoprost, and tafluprost are examples of:", options: ["Suspensions", "Prodrugs requiring hydrolysis to active FP-receptor agonists", "Preservatives", "Antibiotics"], correct: 1, explanation: "These prostaglandin-analogue prodrugs are hydrolyzed to their active acid forms in the eye." },
  { id: 43, question: "Valacyclovir is a prodrug of:", options: ["Ganciclovir", "Acyclovir", "Penciclovir", "Foscarnet"], correct: 1, explanation: "Oral valacyclovir is rapidly converted to acyclovir; famciclovir is a prodrug of penciclovir." },
  { id: 44, question: "A soluble ocular insert differs from an insoluble one in that it:", options: ["Must be removed after use", "Dissolves in the tear film and needs no removal", "Delivers no drug", "Is nonbiodegradable"], correct: 1, explanation: "Soluble inserts dissolve (no removal); insoluble inserts give steadier release but must be removed." },
  { id: 45, question: "The first sustained-release intraocular implant was developed for:", options: ["Diabetic macular edema", "Cytomegalovirus retinitis (the ganciclovir implant)", "Glaucoma", "Age-related macular degeneration"], correct: 1, explanation: "The ganciclovir intravitreal implant for CMV retinitis was the first (discontinued 2015)." },
  { id: 46, question: "The only FDA-approved punctal-plug drug delivery system releases:", options: ["Timolol", "Dexamethasone (0.4 mg over 30 days)", "Latanoprost", "Cyclosporine"], correct: 1, explanation: "A resorbable intracanalicular dexamethasone insert (0.4 mg/30 days) is approved for postoperative inflammation/pain." },
  { id: 47, question: "In a liposome, a water-soluble drug is carried in the:", options: ["Lipid bilayer", "Aqueous interior core", "Outer surface only", "It cannot carry water-soluble drugs"], correct: 1, explanation: "Water-soluble drug dissolves in the aqueous core; a hydrophobic drug intercalates into the lipid bilayer." },
  { id: 48, question: "Iontophoresis enhances ocular drug delivery by:", options: ["Increasing vehicle viscosity", "Using an electrical current to drive charged molecules into tissue", "Blocking the puncta", "Raising the solution pH"], correct: 1, explanation: "Iontophoresis moves charged molecules with an electrical current, giving high local concentration with little systemic absorption." },
  { id: 49, question: "Pharmacogenetics is best defined as the study of how:", options: ["Many genes together affect drug response", "Variation in single genes affects drug efficacy or toxicity", "Drugs are metabolized in the liver only", "Drugs are excreted"], correct: 1, explanation: "Pharmacogenetics focuses on single genes; pharmacogenomics considers many genes." },
  { id: 50, question: "Compared with younger patients, older patients typically have:", options: ["More lean body mass and body water", "Less lean mass, less body water/albumin, more adipose, and declining renal function — extending drug half-life", "Faster drug clearance", "No pharmacokinetic differences"], correct: 1, explanation: "These age-related changes extend the half-life of most systemic drugs and potentiate effects, even at reduced doses." },
];

